column3: // The only visible and controllable indicator is wifi LED.
//  ""wlan"" LED is controllable with GPIO and have proper hole in case.
//  ""power"", ""wan"" and ""lan"" LEDs have proper holes in the case, but can not be controlled with GPIO
//  ""hidden_led_2"" and ""hidden_led_4"" can be controlled with GPIO, but have no proper holes in case
//     ""hidden_led_2"" is between POWER and WAN LEDs
//     ""hidden_led_4"" is between WAN and LAN LEDs
//  ""noconn_led_6"" and ""noconn_led_8"" soldered, but have no proper holes in case and not controlled:
//     ""noconn_led_6"" is between LAN and WLAN LEDs
// LED ""hidden_led_2"" between POWER and WAN leds is controllable with GPIO, but it has no proper hole in case;
// LED ""hidden_led_4"" between WAN and LAN leds is controllable with GPIO, but it has no proper hole in case;
// Place (WAN->ANT) | Num | GPIO | LED name (LuCI)   | Note
//            power | 1   |      |                   | POWER LED. Not controlled with GPIO.
//     hidden_led_2 | 2   | 13   | blue:hidden_led_2 | This LED does not have proper hole in case.
//              wan | 3   |      |                   | WAN LED. Not controlled with GPIO.
//     hidden_led_4 | 4   | 16   | blue:hidden_led_4 | This LED does not have proper hole in case.
//              lan | 5   |      |                   | LAN LED. Not controlled with GPIO.
//     noconn_led_6 | 6   |      |                   | Not controlled with GPIO, possibly not connected
//             wlan | 7   | 15   | blue:wlan         | WLAN LED. Wireless indicator.
//     noconn_led_8 | 8   |      |                   | Not controlled with GPIO, possibly not connected
// There is no LED attached, but currently it can not be disabled
